{"cursor":"7789","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'GxP' is a general term for Good (Anything...) Practice quality guidelines and\nregulations. These guidelines are used in many fields, including the\npharmaceutical and food industries.\n\nThe titles of these good practice guidelines usually begin with \"'G'ood\" and end\nin \"'P'ractice\", with the specific practice descriptor in between. GxP\nrepresents the abbreviations of these titles, where x (a common symbol for a\nvariable) represents the specific descriptor.\n\nA \"c\" or \"C\" is sometimes added to the front of the acroynm. The preceding \"c\"\nstands for \"current.\" For example, cGMP is an acronym for \"current Good\nManufacturing Practices.\" cGMP is the most well known example of a GxP. The term\nGxP is only used in a casual manner, to refer in a general way to a collection\nof quality guidelines.\n","linknr":178,"url":"GxP","recorded":1362567568,"links":19,"instances":["drug_manufacture","business"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Quality|Good"],"headings":["Purpose","Consequences of GxP for information technology","List of GxPs","References","See also"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg/40px-Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["quality","business"],["validation","drug_manufacture"]],"members":["validation","quality"],"related":["Quality_(business)","Pharmacology","Good_Manufacturing_Practice","Pharmaceutical_industry","Information_technology","Pharmaceutical_industry","Litigation","Decade","Digital_signature","Good_Auditing_Practice","Good_Agricultural_Practices","Good_Agriculture_